<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Proposition"
         id="Thm_SpanGivesSubSpace"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Span and subvector space</caption>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>For every subset <math>
               <latex>S</latex>
            </math> of <math>
               <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
            </math>, <math>
               <latex>\span(S)</latex>
            </math> is a subvector space of <math>
               <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
            </math>.</para.body>
      </para>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof type="Proof">
      <proof.block>
         <para>
            <para.body>We need to show that <math>
                  <latex>V:=\span(S)</latex>
               </math> satisfies the 
			<subordinate>
                  <hot>three defining properties</hot>
                  <crossref>
                     <definition.ref definitionID="Def_SubVectorSpace"/>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Look up the defining properties of a subspace</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </crossref>
               </subordinate>
			of a subvector space. If <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> is the empty subset of <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
               </math>, this is so by definition. So it remains to consider the case where <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> is not empty.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>To see that the <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{0}</latex>
               </math>-vector belongs to <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>, 
			<subordinate>
                  <hot>pick any</hot>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>It is possible to pick such a vector because <math>
                              <latex>S</latex>
                           </math> is not empty.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </subordinate>
			vector <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
               </math> in <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>. Then <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{0} = 0\cdot \Vect{v}</latex>
               </math> belongs to <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>To see that <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math> is closed under addition, consider any two vectors <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
               </math> and <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
               </math> in <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>. Then we know that</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.display>
            <latex>\Vect{x} = s_1 \Vect{x_1} + \cdots + s_a \Vect{x}_a\quad \text{and}\quad \Vect{y} = t_1 \Vect{y}_1+\cdots + t_b \Vect{y}_b</latex>
         </math.display>
         <para>
            <para.body>for vectors <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}_1,\dots ,\Vect{x}_a, \Vect{y}_1,\dots ,\Vect{y}_b</latex>
               </math> in <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> and numbers <math>
                  <latex>s_1,\dots ,s_a, t_1,\dots ,t_b</latex>
               </math>. This means that</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x} + \Vect{y}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>s_1 \Vect{x}_1 + \cdots + s_a \Vect{x}_1\ +\ t_1 \Vect{y}_1+\cdots +t_b \Vect{y}_b</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>is also a linear combination of <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> and, hence, belongs to <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>. Thus <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math> is closed under vector addition.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>To see that <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math> is closed under scalar multiplication, consider a vector</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>s_1 \Vect{x}_1 + \cdots + s_a \Vect{x}_a</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>in <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>. If <math>
                  <latex>t</latex>
               </math> is any number, then</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>t \Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>(ts_1) \Vect{x}_1 + \cdots + (ts_a) \Vect{x}_a</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>is also a linear combination of vectors in <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>, hence belongs to <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>. Thus <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math> is closed under scalar multiplication.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>This completes the proof.</para.body>
         </para>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
